    <title>Combined summary - Random order for clients page</title>
    <updated>2023-06-06T06:18:33.985334+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2012-July/001672.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email conversations and discussions are focused on the best way to present information about Bitcoin clients on bitcoin.org. There is a debate about whether to use a feature matrix or prose to describe the clients, with some arguing that feature matrices can be confusing for new users. The potential biases of feature matrices were also discussed, with a suggestion made to have separate matrices for features and security/privacy. The importance of track record for end-users was emphasized, and it was suggested that a well-designed page listing major and vetted clients should be created.The ordering of clients is also debated, with some suggesting randomization and others proposing more sensible choices based on "goodness" determined by someone trusted to understand what is good for users and who has familiarity with the programs. Randomized order was not recommended, but if chosen, it should be done client-side using JavaScript. There were concerns about disputes over the order in which clients were shown, leading to Amir Taaki making a change to randomly order them. However, Gregory Maxwell disagreed and said that the other clients are becoming stable and mature, leading to diversification in the ecosystem. Removing the clients page was deemed unnecessary.Overall, the focus is on providing objective information that is accurate and reliable for users. Suggestions include creating a page listing major and vetted clients, ordering them based on a weighted average of features, security, and goodness for the network, and including both prose descriptions and feature matrices with well-defined categories. A decision assistant setup could also be helpful for inexperienced users. There were discussions about the effectiveness of feature matrices and prose in presenting information about clients. While some argue for a feature matrix, others prefer text that contextualizes the complete feature set. The potential biases of feature matrices in Bitcoin clients are highlighted, with suggestions made to provide users with more detailed information while avoiding overwhelming those who don't want it. Overall, the goal is to provide users with accurate and reliable information about all available options.Additionally, there are discussions about diversification in the ecosystem and the importance of acknowledging alternative clients. The importance of the clients page was emphasized as it contributes significantly to Bitcoin's growth, and Bitcoin.org should remain a neutral resource for the community. The author argues against removing controversial content on a website and proposes a more user-focused approach to decision-making processes. The discussions also touch on issues related to JS randomization, fairness and equality in Bitcoin clients, and the importance of diversity in the Bitcoin network. The proposal is to have separate matrices for features and security/privacy on the Bitcoin Wiki, along with explanations of basic client types, to provide users with more detailed information while avoiding overwhelming those who don't want it. It was suggested that directing people to other clients can improve the user experience. The importance of the clients page was emphasized as it contributes significantly to Bitcoin's growth, and Bitcoin.org should remain a neutral resource for the community. There were also debates about the best way to manage the website and decision-making processes that are not influenced by internal politics.</summary>
